segments.text: testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing one two three four five this is Friday December 28th and we're in El Paso and I have the honor and pleasure of chatting with Larry Francis class of 55 Larry to introduce yourself to anyone that might hear this tape or read the transcription give a biographical
summary of you and your life before you got to A&M.
Where, what did mom and dad, what did they do?
Where'd y'all live?
I was born in San Antonio, Texas in 1933.
My parents were born there and my father worked for the General Electric Company there and was transferred to El Paso in 1941 just for World War II.
So I
completed almost all of my public education here other than the first grade.
I went to grade school here and graduated from Austin High School in 1951 and I did reasonably well as far as education marks in school and
and had decided though that I was going to A&M probably in about 1939.
Why?
Because my older cousin was in the famous class of 42.
They got his degree handed to him and he managed to stay alive across the Pacific.
And I have a picture in front of their house in San Antonio
in which he has his little Aggie bag with the sticker on the side of it, and I've got his hat on.
So I knew I was going to A&M, I guess, from day one.
And I was very fortunate.
I, uh, I had never been outside of El Paso other than to San Antonio, Texas a few times to see relatives.
I had been as far north as Philmont Scout Ranch once, and my parents took me to A&M and dropped me in my footlocker off that afternoon, and that was a long way from home.
What did, as you recall, did anybody, mom or dad or anybody else, give you advice?
They probably tried.
and I probably thought I knew everything.

But as far as you mean when I arrived at A&M, I think they expected me, number one, my parents were, my dad started out life unloading refrigerators out of boxcars for GE, and he was a clerk here, and he became the branch manager, but we never had a lot of money.
I think about the main thing was they expected me to do well.
I had, as I say, I was in the top 10% of my class at Austin High.
They expected me to do well at A&M, and I enrolled in electrical engineering.
They expected me to not spend any more money than I. I got $5 a week to cover everything, and I remember it was $50, I think, for tuition.
Uh, they expected me to stay out of trouble and get a degree.
Now, you had never visited the campus before you went to...
I'd never been there in my life.
...before you went to enroll.
The only thing I knew about Texas A&M was when I wrote off and got that manual, that book that described everything.
As you, about how long were they there on that drop-off trip?
Did you all spend the night?
No, we had spent the night in Austin, Texas.
And as I recall, I was supposed to be at Sabisa Dining Hall at 10 o'clock on whatever morning it was.
We left Austin that morning early and got there about 9.30.
I went in.
There was a desk.
I paid the fees.
They gave me a room number over in Walton Hall.
We were the first class back on campus, the freshmen from Bryan.
I said, I'm ready.
Y'all might as well leave.
And they looked at me, and so by noon, they were gone.
And that's the last time I saw my guests until Christmas when I came home.
And there must have been somebody then from A&M kind of come in and tell you what to do.
Well, the first one that there obviously was people there at Sabisa that said, well, now you're going to go through registration and you're going to do this and that.
I don't remember too much about that.
I do remember going over and putting that footlocker in that room.
Now, I was fortunate.
One of my high school classmates was also my roommate at A&M.
He didn't finish there.
And the first thing I remember was that night when the two, the juniors in my outfit, we had this meeting, I remember.
And I thought, my God, what have I gotten into down here?
And that's probably the first impression

real impressionable meeting i had now is this when they explained to you they explained to me just how it was going to be and and as i recall and i was trying to think about this there was probably 25 or 30 graduates of austin high that enrolled down there at that time which was quite a few i think we had more than any time before
There was probably another eight or 10 from El Paso High.
I think there was about seven or eight from Isleta.
And out of all of those, probably only eight of us graduated.
When your parents drove away, how much money did you have in your pocket?
Do you remember?
It wasn't much.
Probably no more than $10.
My dad would send me $5 in cash in an envelope.
The MSC had just opened.
McKee had built it, and it had opened in May.
I didn't know Robert E. McKee built that.
Yeah.
Marvelous.
McKee built it, and it just opened.
There were two post offices.
One was in there.
It's no longer where it was.
It was up in the front at that time.
The other one is still the old one at Northgate.
Mm-hmm.
And I had a box over at the MSC, even though I was at Walton.
I'd go over there and get my five bucks on Friday.
I'd get my haircuts, everything out of that.
Now, as far as you recall, about what did it cost total to attend a semester or a year?
Room, board, tuition, books.
Books were, at that time, were about, it was just about as expensive as anything.
As I recall, it seems like for a semester you could go to school down there for about $500.
As you walked around the campus, describe the campus.
Well, it was at a process of change at that time.
The central part remains somewhat similar.
Out in front of the academic building, there were two old buildings.
One was Austin Hall where the
The ROTC headquarters was.
It subsequently moved to a building, and it's probably not there.
They called it the Trigon over near Rudder.
It's still there.
Guyon was there.
There was another one, a sister building to Austin on the other side of the main walk coming in.
That one had just been torn down.
They tore Austin down, I guess, my sophomore year.
Electrical engineering was in Bolton Hall.
It's no longer there.
and its mirror image was a civil engineering building.
Nagel.
Nagel.
The old M.E.
building and shops, and that's probably the first time we all got in trouble, and I don't know how we lived.
The M.E.
shops were over there, the old sawtooth kind of factory building.
A classmate in my outfit freshman year, Buck Gay,
climbed up on the water tower to paint it one night, and believe it or not, fell off.
And went right through the roof of the M.E.
shop.
That was that asbestos board.
Left an outline, hit the floor, and he's still alive.
In that footlocker, what kind of stuff did you bring with you?
I didn't have a lot.
That was one of the reasons that people like me went to A&M.
You didn't have to have a lot of clothes.
So I've often thought about that.
I had maybe a couple of sports shirts and a pair of pants outside of underwear and toiletries.
I'm not even sure that I had a heavy coat of any kind, because I remember everywhere I went, I had to wear that big old wool coat.
And describe your room, what you and your roommate created.
Well, it was one of those that, Walton's still there, and I don't know when it was built, but it was kind of a unique, and there was a couple of them on campus.
There were two rooms and a bath between the two rooms.
So instead of one big common bathroom, you had a
And they were poured kind of marble floors and tile walls, and you had a bunk bed arrangement, a steel bunk bed, two desks, and two chairs, and that was it.
Were you allowed to have a radio?
Yes, I think we were, except it had to be off.
by a certain time.
You know, we came back, freshman year, you had to start studying right after, I think it was at seven, you had to start studying.
And lights out, I think it was like 10 or 10.30, something like that.
And of course, in electrical engineering, that's all I did was study.
Now, you registered by standing in line at Sabisa?
At Sabisa.
How did you decide what courses to take?
Who advised you?
Well, as I recall, that was all
predetermined.
If you said you were going to study electrical engineering, they say here's what you have to take.
In fact, it was in that book.
One of the things that my children, two of them went there and I've often discussed with them and now my grandchildren hopefully are going to go there.
They allowed us to take a lot more hours than they take now.
I remember
I used to take a minimum of about 17 or 18.
I think one year I took 21.
The reason I'm chuckling, the typical student today thinks that 12 hours is a full load and that 15 is a heavy load, and therefore they don't expect to graduate in five years.
They don't.
Maybe five and a half.
And I tell them, no, our parents are going to kick our fanny if we didn't finish in four.
Oh, yeah.
I stayed on, I got a master's degree there.
And I graduated in May and stayed on with summer school, both sessions in the fall and the spring, and got out with a second degree a year later.
And that fall, do you remember any of those first year classes?
Were any of those important to you?
Describe some of those people, some of those courses.
I remember the chemistry class that I hated dearly because the lab was on Friday afternoon, starting at 3.
And if you want, my wife, who I had started dating in junior high, went to TSCW, which was considered the sister school.
I had no car or anything, so on Friday evening, once a month, I'd hitchhike all the way to Denton.
Well, I couldn't do that with that chemistry class.
And, you know, the mechanical drafting.
I must have lost 20 pounds down there because mechanical drafting was in the barracks south of, just at Southgate almost, well down below the stadium.
And, you know, you'd have a class at the academic building.
Then you had to be down there carrying that.
We had those fishing tackle boxes with all of our drafting tools carrying your T-square.
And away you'd go.
And physics.
I liked physics.
I remember that class.
I remember we had a mechanical engineering class of some kind.
I forget what it was.
It wasn't mechanical engineering.
I enjoyed all those classes.
And I made the best grades I made at A&M my freshman year.
I made straight As my freshman year.
What was the key to making those good grades?
I had never studied so hard, and that's one of the things I think that A&M did.
You know, it was called Huntsville on the Brazos and this, that, and the other.
There was nothing else to do.
And if you were, if you, I knew I had to get that degree.
My cousin had gotten a degree, but out of that huge family of ours on both sides, I was the second one in that whole family that got a degree.
And I had to get that degree.
So I studied.
Were there any of those teachers that first year that you now realize made a dent in your heart or your brain?
A lot of them.
And the irony is one of them was Dutch Dillingham.
His younger brother, who was a lot younger, is a very good friend of mine, still alive, Mike Dillingham, and we go to all the football games.
We have season tickets.
And that's kind of an irony, because Dutch was involved in the first radio broadcast of a football game.
But he was very good.
You know, I don't remember too many of the math professors, freshman, well, I think we took algebra, and I don't remember too many of those.
In those days, you didn't have very many instructors.
You had the professors.
In chemistry, we had an instructor, and I think in math, we had an instructor.
I remember the mechanical engineering, I mean, civil engineering.
That's what it was.
We took surveys.
I remember going around that campus, and I forget his name though, but he was a great guy.
We had a lot of good professors over in the E-Department in those days, Hallmark.
And did you engineering majors think that you were the cream of crop?
Was there a great pride in the engineering?
Well, maybe some of them did.
I guess I never gave it that much thought.
I think we, I think the engineering majors thought they studied more than the rest of them, but I don't know that we thought we were any smarter than the rest of them.
What was your outfit?
What outfit were you in?
Well, I was in the Air Force, and I was in, originally in, and I forget the outfit number as a freshman.
We were up in, as I say, in Walton.
Then I was in Squadron 14.
Did it have a nickname?
In those days, we didn't.
And then my junior year, I was on the fourth group staff.
And then I was going to be the CEO of the fourth group.
But my wife, who was a lot smarter than I was, graduated from college in three years with a teaching degree.
So that summer, we decided to get married.
And she taught high school in Bryan, Texas.
In fact, taught Travis Bryan III in the first grade.
Really?
Oh, my, my.
So we rented a house first from old man Lauderstein, and then from Chris Gronemann, who was head of the industrial engineering department, built some new duplexes south side there.
So I was in what was called the day ducks my senior year.
Back to your freshman year, when did you and your buddies get introduced to A&M traditions?
When did they line you all up in the hallway and start explaining things to you and how it was going to be and what was going to happen?
Well, that was the first night.
Describe that.
Well, you know, they got us at attention.
And, of course, none of us really knew how to get
And they were screaming at us, and they were hollering at us.
And they went through all of this about what we were going to do and what we weren't going to do, and that we were the most ignorant people in the world.
We weren't going to walk on the grass.
And it went on and on and on and on.
And I think what I saw, my older cousin who had graduated
used to come home in 39, and I remember they beat their rear end constantly down there.
I think I was prepared, and so it didn't bother me as much as a lot of them left within two or three days.
Did you ever think about leaving?

I wanted I told my dad when I came home Christmas I said I uh this is just too tough and I think I want to come home and he says well you can think all you want but you're going back that's your that's your only option so that was the best thing that ever happened I enjoyed my time at A&M right now you didn't have that freshman year particularly you didn't have any troubles with grades
Explain why you did so well that first year academically.
You know, I don't know why.
I think my makeup is I'm kind of persistent.
And there was a very close friend of mine.
His father was in the Isleta school system.
He was our class salutatorian at Austin High.
Brilliant.
And he was in my outfit, too, from here.
And his grades were terrible, and he had to leave.
He ended up going to the University of Virginia, and I never heard about him again, but I assume he did quite well.
He just wasn't, he wasn't smart.
Just didn't fit.
I think there was a lot of them were in constant fear, though.
Now, was there any circumstance, any event or situation that first semester or first year where you needed to go seek advice from anybody?
No.
I don't think in the four years I was there.
I only had one time that I almost got kicked out of school.
I was in the Ross Volunteers.

and they you know it was they beat our butt one night at a party and the administration heard about it and there were about 10 of us sitting on we thought this was going to help on blocks of ice in the restroom in the dorm and they came in and of course did an inspection and caught every one of us

and it took them about three days you know because they we were we knew if you allowed it to happen it was much your fault as oh okay and we I thought we were all gonna get kicked out of school who was the president during that time Harrington did you ever have a class with him by chance no see he goes way back to class of 22 his wife's still living Ruth

from Plano, and the Harrington family in Plano was almost the key, key family of what was then a little bitty country farming town, because I lived in Garland until I was 10, only about eight miles away, and they had the farm oil dealership, a furniture store, and they were also the morticians, so that...
They were everything.
The coming and going, they took care of.
At that hazing, though,
Well, did they beat you all for a purpose or was it just part of the initiation?
Well, it wasn't even an initiation.
We had a beer bust.
The RVs marched, I don't know if they still do, in the King Rex Parade as the honor guard and we came back from that and we had this end of the year kind of April beer bust somewhere off campus.
You were a junior?
I was a junior.
And the seniors decided it was time that, and that, it was just one of those things.
What kind of paddles did they use?
Big boards, you know, the ones that are cut out.
About a one by six?
No, no, they're, yeah, well, they were one inch lumber, you know, cut.

about that long and do you remember about how many spats did everybody get oh about six or seven something like that and then did all of the sophomore i mean all the juniors yeah but only about six or eight of us for some reason got caught the other ones either disappeared conveniently or i don't remember what happened did that did the administration call y'all in oh yeah
and told us that you knew what the consequences were.
All right.
According to the administration, you should have just refused.
Which would have meant?

you wouldn't have been accepted you're not going to do that and they knew that i think they were just trying to put the fear of god into it let's see back to uh back to that uh that freshman year though oh there was a picnic by the way you go back to battalion at that time it would have been in uh 19 spring of what 54.
They had a big cartoon on the editorial page of us sitting on blocks of ice.
Now Jim Earl's not one of your contemporaries, is he?
Cadet Slouch?
Yeah, he started while I was there.
They live not far from us and we see them quite often.
Back to that freshman year, did they haul you all out in the hallway and give you lectures and
Well, they couldn't call us in the hallway and walk.
Oh, that's right.
Well, where did they, yeah, where did they?
They had that day room up there that they got us all in.
And that's where you'd hit a brace?
Yeah.
What kinds of things did they make you fish do?
Oh, what was it?
We were always doing something.
Push-ups?
No, you know, there wasn't that much of that.
Things were, one of the things I've noticed, they've kind of formalized or made this more in the Corps.
These push-ups they do, things were kind of laid back.
Cadet Slouch epitomized the Corps in that day.
We were always running errands and for those guys, cleaning their room.
I don't know how many times I had to clean that guy's room.
Describe for your fish year your routine on a class day.
What time did you get up, what did you do when, and when did you finally get to go to sleep?
Well, you get up, as I recall, I think about 6 a.m. And you get cleaned up, shaved, and out in formation.
to march to every meal.
Boy, that got old, especially when it was raining, and it rains a lot.
And in those days, we had those ponchos.
We didn't have raincoats.
We had those doggone ponchos, and they called them pisspots, the helmet liners, and your uniform.
And we'd march up from the dorms down below Walton, and we'd march over to Sebesa.
for breakfast.
Now, a lot of the guys who just couldn't get up in one of that extra 10 or 15 minutes would have on nothing but underwear.
And if it was raining hard, the upperclassmen were about as out of it as we were, and they wouldn't see.
And the way we'd go, you'd come back and clean up your room.
And by then, it was time for your 8 o'clock class.
Now, when did you clean up that upperclassman's room?
Oh, usually at night.
Oh, okay.
And I did, you know, my roommate and I cleaned that guy, PJ.
Well, I'm not going to say.
Anyway, we cleaned his room.
Neat guy, really was.
And he was a little baddie rooster and immaculate.
Uniforms, you know.
And after about, I remember it was just before Christmas, we'd had about enough of that.
So we both filled trash cans with water, went over there in the middle of the night.
He didn't lock his door, walked in there and dumped it all over him and took off.
Of course, he found us real quick because we dropped the ash cans and he knew who they belonged to.
And what punishment did you get then?
Oh, he had us out.
The bull ring, they called it on Saturday, marching tours.
and we had to clean the room even more, and we were always running errands.
But you didn't mention a paddle or anything like that?
You know, I never got my butt beat at A&M other than at the RVs.
I'm glad you mentioned that.
Now, there was a lot of them that did, but the guys in the outfits I wore,
What other kind of good bull do you remember when you were a fish that you or anybody else did?
Oh, gosh.
What do I remember?
I remember going over to UT in Austin my freshman year before the game, and then about six of them, I think, decided after a few
few too many beers.
Of course, we were only eighteen years old.
Going over there and painting their fountain or something.
Now, I didn't go, and they got caught, and they came back to school all shaved and painted orange.
You know, I can remember
going up to see my wife, who's now my wife, and I never had any money.
And I loved to go up there because they had good food at the time, I thought.
And Tom Dahlheit, who went to Isleta High, was on the track team here at Isleta, was on the track team at A&M.
He went up there with me.
And we never had any money, and we'd come back on Sunday hitchhiking.
We got as far as Waco.
Somebody gave us a ride to Waco, out in the country south of Waco.
We were waiting for another ride, and we were starving to death.
Tom was raised on a farm.
He looks over the fence, and here's a bunch of chickens.
He says, I'm going to fix this lunch.
I said, what are you going to do?
He went over that fence and grabbed a chicken and wrung its neck, plucked it, and then went under the viaduct there and built a fire

roasted that chicken i almost threw up i mean that's how poor i guess we were i don't know in hitchhiking how long did it normally take you to go to or from then oh at least five hours and where was the hardest place to get through dallas or fort worth well we'd go through dallas no but i mean was it hard to get a ride through dallas
I don't recall it being that hard.
I think the hardest place was getting out of Denton sometimes, and a lot of times you'd get to Waco or someplace and have a hard time getting home.
I remember two or three of us were picked up on the north side of Dallas one Sunday morning about 9 o'clock by a guy in a big Cadillac.
Turns out he wasn't a very savory character, I don't think.
And, you know, we wore our uniforms.
He thought we were stupid.
